nd, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England":"Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"5 March 1435–1508":"5 March 1435–1508","1435–1508":"1435–1508","1439–1485":"1439–1485","1462–Male":"1462–Deceased","1467–Female":"1467–Deceased","1472–1539":"1472–1539","1476–1534":"1476–1534","1396–1435":"1396–1435","1462":"1462","1396":"1396","1472":"1472","5 March 1435":"5 March 1435","1534":"1534","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1485":"1485","Abt. 1485":"about 1485","after 16 November 1471":"after 16 November 1471","1508":"1508","1539":"1539","1439":"1439","Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England","Lichfield, Lichfield District, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England":"Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Stanley, including those in Yorkshire, Staffordshire, Derbyshire, Durham, Gloucestershire, and Wiltshire, named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. This English name has been established in Ireland since the 13th century where it was Gaelicized as <b>de Stainléigh</b>.","English: possibly also a variant of <b>Stoneley</b>, a habitational name from Stoneley Green in Burland (Cheshire), Stoneleigh (Warwickshire), or Stonely in Kimbolton (Huntingdonshire), all named with Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Americanized form of any of various like-sounding names in other languages, for example Polish   Stanislawski  , Greek   Anastasiou  , and Serbian <b>Stojadinov</b> (patronymic from the personal name <i>Stojadin</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanislawski","meanings":["Polish (<b>Stanisławski</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Stanisław, Stanisławów, or Stanisławice, named with the personal name <i>Stanisław</i> (see   Stanislav  )."]},{"name":"Standley","meanings":["English: variant of   Stanley  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":19,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"George Stanley was born on 5 March 1435, in Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England as the son of Elisabeth de Bar. He married Eleanor Dudley alias Sutton after 16 November 1471. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1508, in Lichfield, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 73, and was buried in Lichfield, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"5 March 1435–1508":"5. märts 1435–1508","1435–1508":"1435–1508","1439–1485":"1439–1485","1462–Male":"1462–Surnud","1467–Female":"1467–Surnud","1472–1539":"1472–1539","1476–1534":"1476–1534","1396–1435":"1396–1435","1462":"1462","1396":"1396","1472":"1472","5 March 1435":"5. märts 1435","1534":"1534","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1485":"1485","Abt. 1485":"umbes 1485","after 16 November 1471":"pärast 16. novembrit 1471","1508":"1508","1539":"1539","1439":"1439","Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England","Lichfield, Lichfield District, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England":"Hammerwich, Staffordshire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"5 March 1435–1508":"5. maaliskuuta 1435–1508","1435–1508":"1435–1508","1439–1485":"1439–1485","1462–Male":"1462–Kuollut","1467–Female":"1467–Kuollut","1472–1539":"1472–1539","1476–1534":"1476–1534","1396–1435":"1396–1435","1462":"1462","1396":"1396","1472":"1472","5 March 1435":"5. maaliskuuta 1435","1534":"1534","1435":"1435","1467":"1467","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1485":"1485","Abt. 1485":"noin 1485","after 16 November 1471":"16. marraskuuta 1471 jälkeen","1508":"1508","1539":"1539","1439":"1439","Lichfield, Staffordshire, England":"Lichfield, Staffordshire, England","Lichfield, Lichfield District, Staff